<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910502-0191</DOCNO><DOCID>910502-0191.</DOCID><HL>   Panel Seeks Stiffer Terms   For Crimes Involving Guns</HL><DATE>05/02/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><IN>LAW AND LEGAL AFFAIRS (LAW)</IN><NS>LAW andamp; LEGAL ISSUES, HEARINGS, RULINGS, LEGISLATION (LAW)</NS><GV>CONGRESS (CNG)JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- A federal commission recommended longerprison sentences for people convicted of crimes involvingfirearms.   The proposed guidelines were drafted by the seven-memberU.S. Sentencing Commission, a judicial agency created byCongress in 1985 to bring more uniformity to federalsentencing. The guidelines will go into effect this fallunless Congress chooses to block them, which isn't expected.</LP><TEXT>   Congress currently is considering several firearms-relatedmeasures, including a bill to require a seven-day waitingperiod before the purchase of a handgun. The measure hasalready cleared the House Judiciary Committee and may come tothe floor as early as next week.   The commission recommended doubling sentences for peoplecommitting crimes with firearms who have been convictedpreviously of violent or drug-related crimes. It alsorecommended doubling sentences for offenses involving illegalmilitary-style assault rifles and for people who illegallysell firearms across state lines. In some instances,sentences would be more than doubled under the newguidelines.</TEXT></DOC>